items.title: Deprecation warning due to invalid escape sequences
items.body:
Deprecation warnings are raised due to invalid escape sequences. This can be fixed by using raw strings or escaping the literals. pyupgrade also helps in automatic conversion : https://github.com/asottile/pyupgrade/

```
find . -iname '*.py' | grep -v example | xargs -P4 -I{} python3.8 -Wall -m py_compile {}
./qtawesome/icon_browser.py:110: DeprecationWarning: invalid escape sequence \.
  reString += "^%s\." % group
```

items.title: Replacing qta.icon() with a reference to a variable in another module doesn't work
items.body:
I'm making an application that uses QtAwesome's icons in two different places: one is the main window, the other is inside a widget that's added later to the same main window.

In an attempt to provide a centralized spot to serve the icons, I created a module called `icons.py`, and inside it, did `import qtawesome as qta` and assigned `qta.icon()` calls to constants:

```
NEW_SONG = qta.icon('mdi.file-plus')
OPEN_SONG = qta.icon('mdi.folder-open')
SAVE_SONG = qta.icon('mdi.content-save')
REWIND = qta.icon('mdi.rewind')
FAST_FORWARD = qta.icon('mdi.fast-forward')
PLAY = qta.icon('mdi.play')
PAUSE = qta.icon('mdi.pause')
...
```

I then imported that module from both places and added references to the constants instead of calling `qta.icon()` directly.

With that done, I start the application, the console shows `UserWarning: You need to have a running QApplication to use QtAwesome!`, and no icons are displayed. I'm fairly certain that the application is already running at that point, since the `icons.py` import (which in turn imports QtAwesome) always happens from the main window, which is always created after the application.

I'm not sure what causes this problem, but it almost looks like the QIcon object is lost in its way across modules. At the same time, my IDE shows that the variables, indeed, refer to QIcon objects:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/29354120/80793952-f3baf200-8b6e-11ea-8482-8b8d8af5573b.png)

Intended vs. actual result: 
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/29354120/80794639-ccfdbb00-8b70-11ea-9619-3983aac12fd0.png)

Is it possible to use QtAwesome in this way?

items.title: Wrong type returned for the icon?
items.body:
Hi,

thanks for the project, and for using some layer of abstraction to make it simpler to support both PySide and PyQt.

I am getting a strange error on my ubuntu 14.04, though, when trying out the simple example in the readme. I am trying to interface with my [PySide project](https://github.com/baudren/noteorganiser), doing the following:

``` python
icon = qta.icon('fa.flag')
button = QtGui.QPushButton(icon, 'New entry', self)  # class instance as parent
```

 but when running, I get the following trace:

``` python
TypeError: 'PySide.QtGui.QPushButton' called with wrong argument types:
  PySide.QtGui.QPushButton(QIcon, unicode, Editing)
Supported signatures:
  PySide.QtGui.QPushButton(PySide.QtGui.QWidget = None)
  PySide.QtGui.QPushButton(PySide.QtGui.QIcon, unicode, PySide.QtGui.QWidget = None)
  PySide.QtGui.QPushButton(unicode, PySide.QtGui.QWidget = None)
```

The `QIcon` is probably coming from `PyQt`? In anyway, it is not understood as `PySide.QtGui.QIcon`.

If that helps to narrow down the problem:
- it seems to be absent on windows 8.1
- I don't have PyQt installed on my system, only PySide

Thanks in advance!
